Part 1: Getting to know ggplot

ggplot is a powerful and popular graphing toolbox for R. Well use it throughout the semester, and if you continue working with data in R, it will be an invaluable tool for you. ggplots syntax (the way it is typed) is strange at first, and there is definitely a learning curve. Well start with the basics. Because ggplot allows flexibility in how its commands are expressed, there are a variety of coding styles. If you are already comfortable with ggplot, you may write your code however you like. Take my suggestions in the assignment as one style that I find works for me.

Well work with a dataset containing arrest records in NYC. Download and extract the arrests.csv file from Courseworks. The dataset contains rows that are NYPD arrests from Jan 2020 through Jan 2021. Read the dataset into R using read.csv() (NOTE: Dont use readr functions such as read_csv() for this, as some of the later steps may not make sense). Also, the beginning of a script is a good place to load libraries/packages youll use. If you dont have ggplot2 installed yet, do so by running install.packages('ggplot2').

library(ggplot2)
arrests = read.csv('arrests.csv')

The essential steps in designing a ggplot visualization are: (1) Initiating the plot with a call to ggplot() (2) Linking the data columns to a coordinate system (axes) with aes() (3) Displaying the data with a geom or shape, such as geom_point()

The choice of geom often requires the most thought, as certain geoms only work for certain types of data. For example, a histogram, that shows a distribution of values of a continuous variable wouldnt work a categorical variable, such as state or neighborhood.

Histograms are among the best tools to explore and summarize continuous data. Below, use ggplot to make a histogram of precincts where arrests are made (ARREST_PRECINCT). (yes, this isnt really a continuous variable, but we can treat it as such here) First call ggplot(), passing in the arrests data frame as the only argument. Then, link the precinct variable to the x axis by giving x = ARREST_PRECINCT as the argument to aes(). Finally, add a histogram geom with geom_histogram() - it will work with no arguments, but have a look sometime at what arguments are available. Place each function call on its own code line, and include a + at the end of each line except the last one. If you end a line with + and hit enter/return, R will automatically indent the next line.

ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = ARREST_PRECINCT) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

From this plot, does it appear that some precincts have higher arrest rates than others?

In ggplot, aesthetics are the mapping of the data to the graphs visual canvas. They link data columns to axes. This is separate from the geoms that represent data points. Below, make a box plot showing arrest precincts by race by linking PERP_RACE to the x-axis and ARREST_PRECINCT to the y-axis in aes(). Use geom_boxplot() with no arguments to create the boxes.

ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = PERP_RACE, y = ARREST_PRECINCT) +
  geom_boxplot()

To illustrate the difference between aesthetics and geoms, copy+paste your code above, but substitute geom_boxplot() with geom_point(). Youll see the axes have not changed, but instead of the data represented by boxes, there are now individual points for each observation. Its very difficult to make sense of, because all the points are stacked on top of each other! Copy+paste again, and substitute geom_point() with geom_jitter(). The jitter geom modifies geom_point() by randomly shifting the points along one or both axes - this can be useful when data are densely packed. One more time, copy+paste again and substitute geom_jitter() for geom_violin(). A violin plot is a handy way to visualize distributions - the bubble is wide where data are concentrated, and narrow where data are sparse. (Note that RStudio will print one figure per code chunk. You can navigate multiple figures by clicking the thumbnails below the chunk)

# Use geom_point() here
ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = PERP_RACE, y = ARREST_PRECINCT) +
  geom_point()

# Use geom_jitter() here
ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = PERP_RACE, y = ARREST_PRECINCT) +
  geom_jitter()

# Use geom_violin() here
ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = PERP_RACE, y = ARREST_PRECINCT) +
  geom_violin()

Notice that you didnt change the aesthetic aes() mapping here - only the shapes, geom, used to represent the data. The choice of the best representation often comes down to the geom.

You can map data to aesthetics (axes) other than just x- and y-axes. Often well use color to distinguish groups or represent data values. Below, copy+paste the boxplot you made above, but link the PERP_SEX variable to an additional aesthetic. Try it with both color = PERP_SEX and fill = PERP_SEX (do only one or the other, then see what happens if you have PERP_SEX linked to both color and fill)

ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = PERP_RACE, y = ARREST_PRECINCT, fill = PERP_SEX) +
  geom_boxplot()

How are color and fill different?

Part 2: Making the visualization look good

So far weve covered how to represent data using aesthetics and geoms. But a crucial aspect of visualizations is that they must be legible and clear to anyone who will view them. Remember, the main point of producing a visualization is to communicate a result to other people! Importantly, a clean and clear graph buys you credibility, making it more likely others will take your work seriously, and hopefully learn something new.

Theres a lot we can do to clean these plots up. Copy+paste one of the plot codes you made above into the chunk below (any one you like except the histogram). Assign the plot to an object called plt or p or some short name. When you do this, RStudio wont display the plot - instead youll see the plot object in your environment. You can now continue modifying that plot with p + your_functions(). You can see the plot anytime by typing the objects name, p, and executing.

# p = ggplot() # your plotting code here

p = ggplot(arrests) +
  aes(x = PERP_RACE, y = ARREST_PRECINCT) +
  geom_boxplot()

p     # View the plot

First off - on my computer, I cant read the axis labels because theyre too long and they overlap. We can get full control over axis styling using themes. Themes control the visual appearance of the plot that is not data (which is controlled by aesthetics). By accessing theme elements, we can adjust tick marks, tick spacing, tick labels, background colors, gridlines, axis lines, and so on. Each theme property has an element associated with it, such as element_line() for line objects like tick marks, or element_text() for text objects like tick labels. These can be a bit tricky to understand at first, so run the code chunk below, and study the structure of the theme() line for a moment.

# Reassign the plot to itself, to store the changes we're about to make
p = p +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

# Now view the plot again
p

What changed in the plot? Play around with the arguments to element_text() to get a feel for what they do. (try setting angle to 45 or 180, and hjust to 0.5 or 0)

While were on themes, lets fix up a few more things. Often, youll change many thematic/styling elements at once, so it can be useful to group them (thats my opinion!). Rather than call theme() many times, we can set all our theme changes in one theme() call. Run the code below to see the changes Ive started. Complete the theme() call by giving an element_line() to both axis.line.x and axis.line.y. You can run ?theme in the console to see the theme properties you have control over, and, for example ?element_line to see what element properties you can customize. The possibilities are endless!

p = p +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        axis.line.x = element_line(),
        axis.line.y = element_line())
p

ggplot has many pre-built custom themes as well, which you can quickly add with, for example, theme_bw(), or theme_classic(). Look online for a full list. But if you learn how to work with theme properties, you will have complete control of how your plot looks! Trust me, its worth the investment.

Anyway, this plot desperately needs clearer axis labels and a title! It couldnt be easier with xlab(), ylab(), and title(). Or, we could do it all at once with labs(), passing in arguments x = '...', y = '...', title = '...'. Below, fix up the axis labels and add a title with either labs() or the more specific labeling functions xlab() etc.

# Be sure to overwrite your plot object by
# assigning it to itself in order to keep the changes
# p = p +
#   your changes
# p

p = p +
  labs(x = 'Race', y = 'Precinct', title = 'Precinct arrests by race')

p

This plot looks better by orders of magnitude. Depending on how youve been proceeding, you may have line art box plots - boxes that are white on the inside, on top of a white background, with black borders. Shapes that are filled with the same color as the background are harder to see and less impactful for a viewer. You may like to fill the box with a slightly more pronounced color (or gray) so the viewer can more easily distinguish differences among groups. You can pass fill = and color = into some geoms - outside of aes() - to give them static colors. See how/if your plot changes when you run the chunk below. (If you are already using fill/color in aes() this may not look great)

p +
  geom_boxplot(fill = 'grey')

In lab, we discussed Edward Tuftes concept of small multiples. This is one way of visualizing crowded data by creating mini-plots that vary along some grouping variable (e.g.state or neighborhood). ggplot has a function facet_wrap that makes plotting small multiples very easy. The code chunk below plots the total number of arrests across time (2020-2021), grouped by NYC borough. Study the code below before you run it, then run and see the resulting plot. The key line here is facet_wrap(~ Borough). I did some wrangling to format dates and get counts of total arrests in each borough at each time point, but facet_wrap() does all the hard work of creating the visualization. I also did some theme clean-up, and added a geom_smooth to show overall trends on top of the noisy raw data.

# WRANGLING
# ---------
# The arrest date is a chr variable, convert it to a datetime that ggplot can work with
arrests$ARREST_DATE = as.Date(arrests$ARREST_DATE, format = '%m/%d/%y')

# Use table() to get counts of rows by date and borough
# Convert the table() output to a dataframe - by default the col names are Var1, Var2 etc
totals = data.frame(table(arrests$ARREST_DATE, arrests$ARREST_BORO))

# Rename the columns for convenience
colnames(totals)[1] = 'Date'
colnames(totals)[2] = 'Borough'
colnames(totals)[3] = 'Count'

# The table() converts the date back to a chr, so turn it back into a datetime type here
totals$Date = as.Date(totals$Date)
# --------- end WRANGLING

# PLOTTING
# ---------
ggplot(totals) +
  aes(x = Date, y = Count) +
  geom_line() +                       # This line shows the raw data for each time point
  geom_smooth(method = 'loess') +     # This adds a smooth curve on top of the raw data
  theme_bw() +                        # Use a built-in theme to make it a little nicer
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 0.5)) +
  xlab('') +                          # The 'Date' x-axis label is redundant - remove it
  facet_wrap(~ Borough)               # Here's the key line that makes "small multiples"
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Were there changes in arrests made throughout 2020? Were any boroughs more or less likely to have arrests than others, on average?
